<span id="freeTextContainer10109469730138306137">I don&apos;t know why I waited so long to revisit Orhan Pamuk! Both <i>My Name is Red</i> and <i>Snow</i> have stayed with me for many years. The conflicts of an extended family in <i>Silent House</i> mirror the political and social world of 1980 Turkey. Pamuk is especially brilliant at capturing the self-destructive psyche of the male cousins. A terrifying and sad novel.</span>
  <span id="freeText10109469730138306137" style="display:none">I don't know why I waited so long to revisit Orhan Pamuk! Both <i>My Name is Red</i> and <i>Snow</i> have stayed with me for many years. The conflicts of an extended family in <i>Silent House</i> mirror the political and social world of 1980 Turkey. Pamuk is especially brilliant at capturing the self-destructive psyche of the male cousins. A terrifying and sad novel.</span>
