    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2635579686" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2635579686" />
    <a title="Sumant Salunke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67492317-sumant-salunke"><img alt="Sumant Salunke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599239245p2/67492317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2635579686?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sumant Salunke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sumant Salunke" href="/user/show/67492317-sumant-salunke">Sumant Salunke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780307402653" href="/book/show/13531059-silent-house">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2635579686" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14437676949843799420">I didn’t really enjoy the first half of the novel, I think it took too long to get off the ground and while I found the writing good, it wasn’t anything to write home about. But in retrospect, it’s clear that Pamuk was building up these prototypes—bitter widow, servile dwarf, alcoholic academic, reckless teenagers—just to complicate and break them down in the second half, where the book really took off. I thought the structure of the book phenomenal, with its intricate parallels, contrasts and s</span>
  <span id="freeText14437676949843799420" style="display:none">I didn’t really enjoy the first half of the novel, I think it took too long to get off the ground and while I found the writing good, it wasn’t anything to write home about. But in retrospect, it’s clear that Pamuk was building up these prototypes—bitter widow, servile dwarf, alcoholic academic, reckless teenagers—just to complicate and break them down in the second half, where the book really took off. I thought the structure of the book phenomenal, with its intricate parallels, contrasts and subtle commentary. Pamuk captures the schizophrenia of a third world country struggling with history and development, and the violence these discourses espouse through his cast of characters who reaffirm or complicate each other’s beliefs, and the narrative web is revelatory and intricate. This was a really dense book, but it wasn’t really intellectually demanding or emotionally taxing. I think the density comes from the subtle judgment that lurks beneath the surface for his characters and their obsessions, none of which are heading towards anything positive. The only character Pamuk allows us to like, if only through pity, is Recep, and the solitude of Fatma is gorgeously rendered. I need to reread this again without haste to fully understand and appreciate it, but I am definitely looking forward to reading more Pamuk. /3.5/</span>
  <a data-text-id="14437676949843799420" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


